<paragraph id="E97036DD3F76FFE1FF76FBA9FD15FBAB" blockId="67.[151,1437,1071,1710]" box="[151,757,1071,1098]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">
Size. Maximum size 
<quantity id="2E379B383F76FFE1FE65FBA9FE29FBAB" box="[388,457,1071,1098]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" unit="cm" value="10.0">10 cm</quantity>
total length (Miller 1986).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1D565563F76FFE1FF26FBD5FDE9F94C" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F76FFE1FF26FBD5FE46FAC0" blockId="67.[151,1437,1071,1710]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">
Morphology. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F76FFE1FE80FBD5FCE8FB8C" bold="true" box="[353,776,1107,1133]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">D VI + I,13–16; A I,12–15; P 18–19</emphasis>
(Miller 1986). Moderately large goby with subcylindrical body, laterally compressed towards caudal fin, head moderately large. Snout large and blunt. Eyes dorsolateral, interorbital space narrow. Caudal peduncle deep, but lower than body depth. Dorsal fins of similar height, the first dorsal fin may be slightly higher, with more or less rounded edge and no elongate spines. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F76FFE1FB5EFB39FE20FB1C" bold="true" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Caudal fin slightly pointed, almost rounded.</emphasis>
Predorsal area and nape scaled (Miller 1986). 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F76FFE1FC22FB65FE46FAC0" bold="true" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Scales large, visible on body and usually also on predorsal area.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F76FFE1FF26FAADFF00FA37" blockId="67.[151,1437,1071,1710]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">
Live coloration. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F76FFE1FE9FFAADFE79FA88" bold="true" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Body with 2 longitudinal rows of gray-brown to orange-brown spots, more or less overlaid with yellow or orange</emphasis>
, one row along back and another along lateral midline; smaller spots of the same color (and not lines) on head (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F76FFE1FE91FAF5FE24FA6C" box="[368,452,1395,1421]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1061,1085]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1037]" captionTargetId="figure-19@22.[151,1436,181,1037]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 17. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Lesueurigobius friesii. Photo by R. Svensen, Stavanger, Norway." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601619" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601619/files/figure.png" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F76FFE1FE38FAF5FBFFFA50" bold="true" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Both dorsal fins and upper half of caudal fin with yellow to orange spots; second dorsal-fin edge yellow to orange with a blue to whitish submarginal band</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F76FFE1FBD1FA11FAA1FA50" author="Moen, F. E. &amp; Svensen, E." box="[1072,1345,1431,1457]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" refId="ref61908" refString="Moen, F. E. &amp; Svensen, E. (2004) Marine fish and invertebrates of Northern Europe. KOM, Kristiansund / AquaPress, Southendon-Sea, Essex, 608 pp." type="book" year="2004">Moen &amp; Svensen 2004</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F76FFE1FAAFFA11FF34FA37" author="Louisy, P." pageId="67" pageNumber="68" refId="ref60639" refString="Louisy, P. (2015) Europe and Mediterranean Marine Fish Identification Guide. 3 rd Edition. Eugen Ulmer Ed., Paris, 512 pp." type="book" year="2015">Louisy 2015</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
